         <h1>Barnard Hughes, Character Actor, Dies at 90 </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Barnard Hughes , a Tony - and Emmy-award-winning actor who was well-known for playing warm-hearted if not always serious-minded father figures , died yesterday in New York . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 90 . <br><blue>3</blue>His death was confirmed by his son , the director Doug Hughes . <br><blue>4</blue>Though Mr. Hughes made his acting debut in 1934 at age 19 and already had a solid career in theater and television work , it was the 1978 Broadway production of Hugh Leonard 's '' Da '' that gained him his reputation as a skilled character actor , with a particular gift for jolly old Irishmen whose cheerfulness is tinged with melancholy . <br><blue>5</blue>Mr. Hughes played the title role , that of an exasperatingly affable and unambitious Irish widower who haunts the memories of his emigrant son . <br><blue>6</blue>Walter Kerr , writing about '' Da '' in The New York Times , said Mr. Hughes was '' masterly in the role of a lifetime , working skillfully as a watchmaker with every jewel in place . '' <br><blue>7</blue>John Simon , in New York magazine , said that Mr. Hughes '' gives one of the greatest performances of this or any year . '' <br><blue>8</blue>Mr. Simon continued : '' Put this right alongside the achievements of the Gielguds , Oliviers and Richardsons . '' <br><blue>9</blue>Mr. Hughes beat out Hume Cronyn , Frank Langella and Jason Robards for the best-actor Tony that year and also won a Drama Desk award . <br><blue>10</blue>He did a reprise of the role of Da for a 1988 movie version , which also starred Martin Sheen . <br><blue>11</blue>A frequent presence in soap operas and television series of the 1970 's and 1980 's , Mr. Hughes won an Emmy for his portrayal of a senile judge on an episode of '' Lou Grant . '' <br><blue>12</blue>He also starred as an avuncular physician in a short-lived comedy series , '' Doc , '' and as an Irish patriarch in the sitcom '' The Cavanaughs . '' <br><blue>13</blue>He had recurring roles on '' The Guiding Light , '' '' As The World Turns , '' '' All in the Family , '' '' The Bob Newhart Show '' and '' Blossom . '' <br><blue>14</blue>Mr. Hughes also had a long film career , appearing in '' Midnight Cowboy , '' '' The Hospital , '' '' Where 's Poppa ? '' '' <br><blue>15</blue>Oh God ! '' '' <br><blue>16</blue>Tron , '' '' Doc Hollywood '' and numerous television movies . <br><blue>17</blue>Barnard Aloysius Kiernan Hughes was born in Bedford Hills , N.Y. on July 16 , 1915 , to Irish immigrants . <br><blue>18</blue>Through high school and his first year at Manhattan College , he worked a series of jobs , including as a salesman at Macy 's and a dockworker , before a friend tricked him into auditioning for a repertory company that performed Shakespeare in high schools . <br><blue>19</blue>He won a tiny role in '' The Taming of the Shrew . '' <br><blue>20</blue>Mr. Hughes soon dropped out of Manhattan College and stayed with the company for two years , eventually playing many of the major Shakespeare roles . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>His death</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (4_25) 	<br><blue>2(1)</blue>: <m_str>Broadway</m_str> (4_29) 	<br><blue>3(29)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Hughes</m_str> (7_11) 	<m_str>Mr. Hughes</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Barnard Aloysius Kiernan Hughes</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (10_1) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (18_5) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_6) 	<m_str>his son , the director Doug Hughes</m_str> (3_6) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (18_12) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (19_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Hughes</m_str> (4_2) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (4_5) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (12_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Hughes</m_str> (11_18) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (11_24) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (18_34) 	<m_str>Mr. Hughes</m_str> (20_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Hughes</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>Shakespeare</m_str> (18_43) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (13_1) 	<m_str>Walter Kerr</m_str> (6_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (5_22) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (4_40) 	<m_str>Shakespeare</m_str> (20_24) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (4_41) 